Create a Git Repository and Push to GitHub
Step 1: Install & Verify Git

Check whether Git is installed:

git --version


If Git is not installed:

Windows: https://git-scm.com/download/win

Mac:

brew install git


Linux:

sudo apt install git

Step 2: Configure Git (One-Time Setup)

Set your username and email:

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your-email@gmail.com"


Verify configuration:

git config --list

Step 3: Create Project Folder
mkdir learning-journey
cd learning-journey

Step 4: Initialize Git Repository
git init


Output:

Initialized empty Git repository

Step 5: Create README.md File

Create file:

touch README.md


Open file (any one):

nano README.md


OR

code README.md


Add content:

# My Learning Journey üöÄ

This repository documents my journey as a software developer.

## What I‚Äôm Learning
- Python & Django
- REST APIs
- Docker & Kubernetes
- Git & GitHub
- System Design

## Goals
- Improve backend engineering skills
- Build real-world projects
- Crack software engineering interviews

## Progress
I will continuously update this repository with my learnings and projects.


Save the file.

Step 6: Check Git Status
git status


Output:

Untracked files:
  README.md

Step 7: Add File to Git
git add README.md


OR add all files:

git add .

Step 8: Commit Changes
git commit -m "Add README describing my learning journey"

Step 9: Create Repository on GitHub

Go to üëâ https://github.com

Click New Repository

Repository name: learning-journey

Choose Public or Private

‚ùå Do NOT add README

Click Create Repository

Step 10: Connect Local Repo to GitHub
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/USERNAME/learning-journey.git


Verify remote:

git remote -v

Step 11: Push Code to GitHub
git push -u origin main


Login if prompted.

Step 12: Verify on GitHub

Refresh GitHub repository

README.md is visible

Commit message appears
